<TITLE> Bangladesh signs a deal to import 50,000 tonnes of rice from India </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 6 (bdnews24.com)  The caretaker government has signed a deal with India to import 50,000 tonnes of rice, a government official said Thursday. The agreement inked Tuesday marks the second 50,000 tonne deal to have been signed with India as part of a pledge made by Indian foreign minister Pranab Mukherjee to export five lakh tonnes of rice to Bangladesh. Mukherjee made the pledge while on a tour of southern Bangladesh in the wake of Cyclone Sidr. "The food directorate of Bangladesh and the West Bengal Essential Commodity Supply Corporation signed a deal Tuesday to import another 50,000 tonnes of rice," said director general of the food directorate Pius D Costa. "The rice shipment is likely to reach Bangladesh by March 30. The previous deal of 50,000 tonnes will arrive by April 15," Costa said. Of the initial one lakh tonnes of rice, 51,000 tonnes will be transported by road, 29,000 tonnes by water, while the remaining 20,000 tonnes will be transported by rail. The price has been fixed at $398 per tonne. Discussions on the outstanding four lakh tonnes of rice are underway, the director general said. On Feb 12, a deal was approved for Bangladesh to import five lakh tonnes of rice and the caretaker government signed a deal on Feb 20 to import 50,000 tonnes of rice. bdnews24.c
